00:45:45,873 --> 00:45:49,038
Excuse me! He's going for it now!

512
00:45:51,794 --> 00:45:54,576
- MAN 1: Oh, please, after you.
- Thank you.

513
00:46:00,532 --> 00:46:02,125
MAN 2: I haven't had breakfast.

514
00:46:12,759 --> 00:46:14,701
This is insanity, Graeme.

515
00:46:14,775 --> 00:46:19,118
You will cripple yourself,
maybe something even worse than that.

516
00:46:35,195 --> 00:46:37,562
Right, you ready? Go!

517
00:46:37,628 --> 00:46:40,945
ANNE: Come on, Graeme!
Come on, Graeme!

518
00:46:52,254 --> 00:46:55,288
MALKY: Go on, Graeme! Go on.

519
00:47:02,848 --> 00:47:06,264
ANNE: Keep going, Graeme!
Come, you're doing great. Go for it!

520
00:47:06,337 --> 00:47:10,232
- Same as yesterday.
- He's a slow starter.

521
00:47:13,187 --> 00:47:17,727
Come on, Graeme! Shift it!
Come on! Move it, Graeme!

522
00:47:21,604 --> 00:47:24,768
Come on, Graeme! Come on, keep going!

523
00:47:24,836 --> 00:47:29,115
- This is where it went wrong yesterday.
- That was yesterday.

524
00:47:32,967 --> 00:47:34,855
ANNE: Come on, Graeme! Move it!

525
00:47:34,919 --> 00:47:37,341
FRANCESCO: He cannot continue like this.
MALKY: Yeah, you're right.

526
00:47:37,415 --> 00:47:38,909
ANNE: Come on, Graeme.

527
00:47:38,983 --> 00:47:41,220
It's time he really started to pile on.

528
00:47:41,288 --> 00:47:43,623
Come away, Graeme!

529
00:47:48,201 --> 00:47:51,366
ANNE: Keep going, baby! Come on!

530
00:47:55,019 --> 00:47:56,710
MALKY: Come on, Graeme!

531
00:47:59,340 --> 00:48:02,275
ANNE: Come on! Move it, Graeme!

532
00:48:08,557 --> 00:48:10,445
MALKY: Come on, Graeme!

533
00:48:11,054 --> 00:48:14,885
- Come on, Graeme!
- ANNE: Come on, keep going, Graeme!

534
00:48:14,959 --> 00:48:19,914
You can do it, Graeme. Come on.
You're nearly there. Come on, Graeme!

535
00:48:24,753 --> 00:48:26,608
Keep going, Graeme!

536
00:48:35,923 --> 00:48:39,186
He's a whole lap up
on where you were at this point.

537
00:48:44,981 --> 00:48:48,844
Come away, Graeme! On you come!

538
00:48:48,918 --> 00:48:52,148
ANNE: Come on, Graeme! Keep going!

539
00:49:04,153 --> 00:49:07,634
MALKY: Come on, Graeme! That's a good...

540
00:49:08,378 --> 00:49:10,233
(GRAEME PANTING)

541
00:49:14,715 --> 00:49:17,236
He's gonna do it. He's actually gonna do it.

542
00:49:17,756 --> 00:49:19,993
- Come on, Graeme, you're gonna do it!
- MALKY: Come on!

543
00:49:20,060 --> 00:49:21,467
You're gonna do it!

544
00:49:27,454 --> 00:49:29,461
MALKY: Go, go! Faster!

545
00:49:29,534 --> 00:49:31,422
Come on, Graeme!

546
00:49:34,783 --> 00:49:36,092
(PEOPLE CLAPPING)

547
00:50:17,384 --> 00:50:18,332
(CHEERING)

548
00:50:38,828 --> 00:50:41,349
- You did it! You did it!
- Bravo!

549
00:50:42,093 --> 00:50:43,369
Yes!

550
00:50:44,269 --> 00:50:45,349
ANNE: You did it!

551
00:50:50,863 --> 00:50:54,825
Congratulations, Graeme!
Absolutely amazing!

552
00:50:54,927 --> 00:50:56,302
On behalf of Specialized,

553
00:50:56,368 --> 00:51:00,941
I'm proud to give you this check,
and to announce a year's sponsorship.

554
00:51:03,441 --> 00:51:04,685
Go on!

555
00:51:23,862 --> 00:51:25,356
- Graeme.
- Malky...

556
00:51:26,709 --> 00:51:29,612
- Just leave him.
- Why? He's missing the party.

557
00:51:33,751 --> 00:51:35,312
(SOBBING)

558
00:51:44,953 --> 00:51:48,020
Graeme, congratulations!

559
00:51:48,538 --> 00:51:52,019
I see you made the front page.
Well, the local paper, anyway.

560
00:51:52,091 --> 00:51:53,782
I just wanted to say thank you
for your help.

561
00:51:53,851 --> 00:51:56,666
Oh, I didn't make much of a contribution.

562
00:51:56,732 --> 00:51:59,896
Which would seem to be the way
in other cases, as well.

563
00:51:59,964 --> 00:52:01,077
What do you mean?

564
00:52:01,149 --> 00:52:04,216
Do you remember what Karl Marx said
about surplus value?

565
00:52:04,286 --> 00:52:05,715
You're looking at it.

566
00:52:05,790 --> 00:52:09,336
Apparently the powers that be
feel that this town is too small

567
00:52:09,406 --> 00:52:12,636
for two congregations
so there's gonna be a merger.

568
00:52:12,703 --> 00:52:16,533
One of the churches is gonna be sold off
to a property developer.

569
00:52:17,152 --> 00:52:20,349
Agnes, go in. Be with you in a minute.

570
00:52:22,561 --> 00:52:25,977
Now, Graeme, I've got work to do.
Will you excuse me?

571
00:52:26,050 --> 00:52:29,596
One of my parishioners,
her husband has just passed away.

572
00:52:29,667 --> 00:52:32,034
She's got a few problems coping.

573
00:53:08,523 --> 00:53:10,149
Hi, sorry we're late.

574
00:53:10,250 --> 00:53:12,672
Guess who kept going on
about keeping inside the speed limit?

575
00:53:12,747 --> 00:53:17,385
What? Well, there's plenty of time.
It doesn't start for another half an hour.

576
00:53:18,125 --> 00:53:20,100
- So, where's Graeme?
- Going for a run.

577
00:53:20,173 --> 00:53:23,435
Said he'd better things to do
than watch a non-event.

578
00:53:25,070 --> 00:53:27,274
<i>MAN ON TV: The English rider,
Chris Boardman,</i>

579
00:53:27,342 --> 00:53:28,869
<i>Great Britain's Olympic champion</i>

580
00:53:28,943 --> 00:53:33,995
<i>is certain to break the one-hour record
so recently established by Graeme Obree.</i>

581
00:53:34,063 --> 00:53:35,493
<i>Here he goes!</i>

582
00:53:37,233 --> 00:53:41,871
<i>And how devastating this must be
to his arch-rival Obree.</i>

583
00:53:41,937 --> 00:53:43,693
<i>But the world one-hour record holder</i>

584
00:53:44,050 --> 00:53:46,254
<i>is now an Englishman.</i>

585
00:54:21,754 --> 00:54:25,202
Excuse me, excuse me. Sorry.
Sorry, thanks.

586
00:54:25,274 --> 00:54:26,932
- Cheers.
- Cheers, thanks.

587
00:54:33,020 --> 00:54:35,060
Is that not Obree?

588
00:54:38,940 --> 00:54:42,007
Hello, yes, I'd like to make
a reverse-charge call, please.

589
00:54:42,077 --> 00:54:43,987
All right, Graeme?

590
00:54:44,926 --> 00:54:49,367
Yeah, it's 01632960433, that's Prestwick.

591
00:54:51,616 --> 00:54:53,241
I knew it was you.

592
00:54:53,599 --> 00:54:55,771
You're a world champion now,
some shite like that, eh?

593
00:54:55,840 --> 00:54:59,670
- I'm just trying to make a call here.
- Oh, right, aye, aye.

594
00:55:02,338 --> 00:55:04,891
So, what you doing back here then,
champ?

595
00:55:04,962 --> 00:55:06,588
Just come back to show us, did you?

596
00:55:06,658 --> 00:55:07,641
Fuck off.

597
00:55:08,610 --> 00:55:10,945
Hi, Anne, it's me.
Aye, listen I've got a puncture,

598
00:55:11,011 --> 00:55:12,954
could Malky come and pick me up?

599
00:55:14,244 --> 00:55:15,324
Yeah.

600
00:55:16,708 --> 00:55:21,827
Malky? Yeah, I'm back in the valley of
the damned at the pub in the main street.

601
00:55:23,877 --> 00:55:25,765
Aye. Yeah.

602
00:55:26,022 --> 00:55:28,357
Okay. Listen, what did Boardman do?

603
00:55:31,240 --> 00:55:33,062
Seven hundred meters more?

604
00:55:34,024 --> 00:55:37,320
That's more than the margin
I beat Moser's record by.

605
00:55:37,545 --> 00:55:40,098
Right, I'll see you there. Okay, bye.

606
00:55:47,082 --> 00:55:50,858
- What the fuck do you want?
- See, here he is.

607
00:55:51,756 --> 00:55:54,091
Thinks he's the big man now, eh?

608
00:55:55,436 --> 00:55:58,339
But I can remember
what we used to do to him.

609
00:55:58,413 --> 00:56:01,675
Yeah, you made my life hell.
Are you proud of that?

610
00:56:02,574 --> 00:56:05,836
Come on, Graeme, eh?
It's just a bit of fun, mate, that's all.

611
00:56:05,903 --> 00:56:08,773
You wee shites! You dirty bastards!

612
00:56:08,846 --> 00:56:11,181
- Steady!
- Fuck off! Fuck off!

613
00:56:11,279 --> 00:56:12,686
- Go on, then!
- Fuck off!

614
00:56:12,751 --> 00:56:14,923
Supposed to be world champion, man.

615
00:56:14,992 --> 00:56:18,309
You know what?
You take a good fucking look at me.

616
00:56:20,210 --> 00:56:24,204
'Cause this is the closest you'll ever get
to anything worthwhile.

617
00:56:46,743 --> 00:56:51,566
Okay, it's a pain in the arse,
but this is what I was thinking.

618
00:56:53,112 --> 00:56:56,408
We book Hamar again for, say,
the end of the year,

619
00:56:56,472 --> 00:56:58,928
after the Specialized money's run out.

620
00:56:59,001 --> 00:57:02,100
Then we announce
you're going for Boardman's record.

621
00:57:02,169 --> 00:57:04,821
You'll get plenty of people
to sponsor you then.

622
00:57:04,890 --> 00:57:07,225
- We'll get them to make bids.
- No.

623
00:57:07,291 --> 00:57:12,474
They'll be lining up around the block.
The man from nowhere returns.

624
00:57:12,860 --> 00:57:16,919
- The Flying Scotsman rides again.
- No, I'm gonna go for the worlds.

625
00:57:20,861 --> 00:57:25,532
But you don't do that kind of racing.
Not the four-kilometer sprint.

626
00:57:26,334 --> 00:57:27,611
You're a long-distance man.

627
00:57:27,679 --> 00:57:31,062
Fifty-one kilometers or four,
it's still what I do.

628
00:57:32,576 --> 00:57:35,391
Yeah, well...

629
00:57:35,616 --> 00:57:39,741
Right enough, I suppose.
Twelve months to get ready for it.

630
00:57:39,810 --> 00:57:41,915
- I'm going for it this year.
- What?

631
00:57:41,985 --> 00:57:47,038
No, that's... That's totally impossible.
You've only got five weeks.

632
00:57:47,107 --> 00:57:50,686
That's fine. Pressure works for me.

633
00:57:54,788 --> 00:57:57,439
<i>ANNOUNCER: Ladies and gentlemen,
Chris Boardman.</i>

634
00:57:57,957 --> 00:57:59,134
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

635
00:58:13,864 --> 00:58:16,899
As you know,
the annual bring and buy sale

636
00:58:16,969 --> 00:58:20,035
is gonna take place in four weeks' time.

637
00:58:21,194 --> 00:58:23,529
<i>ANNOUNCER: You have to be impressed
that novice Obree</i>

638
00:58:23,594 --> 00:58:27,075
<i>has even made it into the semi-finals
of the World Championship.</i>

639
00:58:27,147 --> 00:58:29,253
<i>But of course,
Boardman's the clear favorite</i>

640
00:58:29,324 --> 00:58:32,673
<i>with his half-million pound,
computer-designed carbon-fiber superbike</i>

641
00:58:32,748 --> 00:58:35,683
<i>that he rode to a gold medal
in the Olympics.</i>

642
00:58:36,685 --> 00:58:40,515
<i>Two riders chase each other from
opposite sides of the track for 16 laps.</i>

643
00:58:40,782 --> 00:58:42,505
<i>It's 4,000 meters of agony.</i>

644
00:58:42,574 --> 00:58:45,095
CROWD: (CHANTING) Five, four, three,

645
00:58:45,166 --> 00:58:48,331
two, one, go!

646
00:58:57,617 --> 00:59:00,814
The Christian band were really rocking
with the Lord...

647
01:00:05,983 --> 01:00:08,569
<i>ANNOUNCER: An astonishing time.</i>

648
01:00:08,640 --> 01:00:10,844
<i>4.:22.668.</i>

649
01:00:11,071 --> 01:00:13,014
<i>A new world record for Graeme Obree,</i>

650
01:00:13,088 --> 01:00:16,122
<i>- who goes through into the final.
- Oh, my God! Oh, my God!</i>

651
01:00:20,065 --> 01:00:22,433
Please forgive that short pause.

652
01:00:23,170 --> 01:00:27,033
I get quite excited by the prospect
of the annual bring and buy sale.

653
01:00:28,196 --> 01:00:31,164
<i>ANNOUNCER: He's beaten
the other semi-finalist, Chris Boardman,</i>

654
01:00:31,236 --> 01:00:33,211
<i>by 2.384 seconds.</i>

655
01:00:33,284 --> 01:00:35,325
You've broken the record.
It's a new world record!

656
01:00:36,421 --> 01:00:38,145
GRAEME: World record? You're joking.

657
01:00:40,581 --> 01:00:42,011
Oh, my legs.

658
01:00:45,223 --> 01:00:47,777
Congratulations, Graeme. Awesome ride.

659
01:00:47,848 --> 01:00:51,427
But you need a better helmet.
Here, use mine for the final.

660
01:00:51,560 --> 01:00:53,121
And the best of luck.

661
01:00:54,729 --> 01:00:55,678
Thanks.

662
01:00:57,065 --> 01:00:59,204
<i>ANNOUNCER: Another world record,
a new world champion.</i>

663
01:00:59,274 --> 01:01:00,900
He won!

664
01:01:02,058 --> 01:01:03,552
Your dad's a world champion!

665
01:01:08,075 --> 01:01:09,253
(COUGHING)

666
01:01:20,718 --> 01:01:21,994
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

667
01:01:34,033 --> 01:01:34,982
Graeme?

668
01:01:39,922 --> 01:01:40,870
Graeme?

669
01:01:40,946 --> 01:01:44,525
Sorry, didn't mean to make you jump,
but the reception's...

670
01:01:45,139 --> 01:01:47,561
And don't we look like a couple of swells.

671
01:01:48,436 --> 01:01:52,266
Listen, Malky,
I know Anne's told you about me.

672
01:01:54,645 --> 01:01:57,067
Good. We should get downstairs, eh?

673
01:01:57,142 --> 01:02:01,169
I just get really down sometimes, and...

674
01:02:02,743 --> 01:02:06,835
Then I tell myself, "Get a grip, man."
And I pull myself out of it.

675
01:02:07,319 --> 01:02:10,735
I mean, there's nothing
really wrong with me, you know.

676
01:02:22,107 --> 01:02:23,449
(WHOOPING)

677
01:02:27,708 --> 01:02:28,788
- Love you.
- Hello.

678
01:02:28,860 --> 01:02:30,070
Hello.

679
01:02:31,260 --> 01:02:32,634
Hey, Anne.

680
01:02:32,924 --> 01:02:35,859
Someone called Bourget's been on
the phone about exhibition rides in France.

681
01:02:35,933 --> 01:02:37,908
Money up front,
accommodation for all of us,

682
01:02:37,981 --> 01:02:40,251
that's what he said,
anything for the new champion

683
01:02:40,318 --> 01:02:42,206
and we can go in our new car.

684
01:02:42,303 --> 01:02:44,059
What's wrong with the one we got?

685
01:02:44,127 --> 01:02:46,942
Have you actually looked at it?
This time we get something a bit better.

686
01:02:52,640 --> 01:02:54,746
MALKY: Think we should turn left here.
KATIE: Malky, who's driving?

687
01:02:54,817 --> 01:02:57,119
- Oh, aye.
- Oh, my God.

688
01:02:57,953 --> 01:02:59,066
Oh, my word.

689
01:02:59,810 --> 01:03:01,152
(ALL APPLAUDING)

690
01:03:03,554 --> 01:03:05,115
ANNE: My goodness, Graeme,
is this for real?

691
01:03:05,187 --> 01:03:06,332
MALKY: Almost like there's some sort of...

692
01:03:06,403 --> 01:03:07,811
I don't have a pen.

693
01:03:14,149 --> 01:03:15,262
Hello.

694
01:03:27,336 --> 01:03:28,929
<i>(SPEAKING FRENCH)</i>

695
01:03:33,064 --> 01:03:35,454
When you tried to beat the record
of the one hour

696
01:03:35,530 --> 01:03:39,327
we all wanted you not to stop ever,
to continue for always.

697
01:03:44,459 --> 01:03:47,329
And even if you had built eyes
for the bicycle,

698
01:03:47,404 --> 01:03:51,016
oh, for sure, they would have been crying.
Yes.

699
01:04:04,335 --> 01:04:07,238
Is it gonna be like this everywhere?

700
01:04:07,312 --> 01:04:09,679
Why not? We deserve it.

701
01:04:10,897 --> 01:04:12,326
You deserve it.

702
01:04:28,436 --> 01:04:30,924
But how can manufacturers
persuade people to buy the right bikes,

703
01:04:30,996 --> 01:04:33,550
when a washing machine on wheels
can break records?

704
01:04:33,621 --> 01:04:36,655
Is he cheating? Drugs, perhaps?

705
01:04:36,726 --> 01:04:39,312
No you can forget that. He takes nothing.

706
01:04:39,382 --> 01:04:42,699
We even tested one of his sandwiches.
Just oranges and sugar.

707
01:04:42,775 --> 01:04:47,347
You know, I loathe seeing him ride.
His position is so grotesque, so ugly.

708
01:04:47,416 --> 01:04:50,034
- And unstable. He fell off last week.
- Oh, yeah?

709
01:04:50,104 --> 01:04:51,479
He fell off?

710
01:04:52,985 --> 01:04:58,867
<i>We have come to the conclusion
that the riding technique ofHerr Obree</i>

711
01:04:58,938 --> 01:05:00,694
<i>could cause him to hurt himself</i>

712
01:05:00,762 --> 01:05:05,171
<i>especially if he were to fall
from his machine at high speed.</i>

713
01:05:05,788 --> 01:05:11,004
<i>And not only that, such an accident could
cause serious injury to other cyclists.</i>

714
01:05:11,101 --> 01:05:14,233
<i>It has therefore been agreed</i>

715
01:05:14,301 --> 01:05:18,361
<i>that the riding position ofHerr Obree</i>

716
01:05:18,430 --> 01:05:22,359
<i>will not be allowed under W...</i>

717
01:05:22,431 --> 01:05:23,379
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

718
01:05:23,455 --> 01:05:26,805
<i>Please, let me finish, under WCF rules.</i>

719
01:05:26,879 --> 01:05:28,571
<i>Thank you very much.</i>

720
01:05:28,672 --> 01:05:30,134
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

721
01:05:34,657 --> 01:05:37,472
It's ridiculous to say it's unsafe,
I've only ever fallen once

722
01:05:37,538 --> 01:05:39,840
and, you know,
it's no miracle machine, either.

723
01:05:39,907 --> 01:05:42,012
- Otherwise I'd win every race.
- No way.

724
01:05:42,082 --> 01:05:46,011
The bike meets all the WCF's regulations,
so now they're just making up new ones.

725
01:05:53,317 --> 01:05:55,008
Okay, I'm going.

726
01:05:55,941 --> 01:05:58,047
You know you don't need to work.

727
01:05:58,694 --> 01:06:00,255
What am I supposed to do
when you're away on tour

728
01:06:00,326 --> 01:06:01,788
with all your cycling groupies?

729
01:06:01,863 --> 01:06:03,870
- I wish.
- Oh, do you now?

730
01:06:04,616 --> 01:06:06,951
The way things are going,
I'll be spending a lot more time at home.

731
01:06:08,713 --> 01:06:10,884
Hagemann and his pals
are really out to get me.

732
01:06:10,953 --> 01:06:13,636
Well, you're a threat.
You got to the top the wrong way.

733
01:06:13,706 --> 01:06:16,608
A few more like you and those people
won't be running things anymore.

734
01:06:16,682 --> 01:06:18,821
- No more gravy train.
- Yeah, that's what makes me so angry.

735
01:06:18,890 --> 01:06:21,312
Well,
that's healthier than being depressed.

736
01:06:23,275 --> 01:06:25,642
You'll find ways to get one up on them.

737
01:06:32,621 --> 01:06:34,563
GRAEME: Now, because of the WCF's
concerns about safety,

738
01:06:34,638 --> 01:06:36,810
I've made a few modifications.

739
01:06:36,878 --> 01:06:41,832
So, ladies and gentlemen I give you
the new, ultra-safe Obree bike.

740
01:06:44,143 --> 01:06:45,637
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

741
01:06:45,904 --> 01:06:47,399
WOMAN: Let's see the back.

742
01:06:49,585 --> 01:06:52,040
He thinks he's so clever, this Mr. Obree.

743
01:06:53,842 --> 01:06:55,369
Stand back, stand back.

744
01:06:58,962 --> 01:07:01,614
We must not allow him
to make fools of us.

745
01:07:01,683 --> 01:07:04,203
But every time we change the rules,
he changes his bike to comply.

746
01:07:04,275 --> 01:07:05,934
Yeah, then you try again.

747
01:07:10,228 --> 01:07:12,815
- That's as far back as it'll go.
- Oh, great.

748
01:07:16,502 --> 01:07:18,869
Your bike contravenes the regulations.

749
01:07:18,934 --> 01:07:22,645
Saddles must be five centimeters
behind the center of the bottom bracket.

750
01:07:22,711 --> 01:07:24,816
Christ's sake,
you inspected the bike yesterday.

751
01:07:24,887 --> 01:07:26,295
You okayed it.

752
01:07:41,435 --> 01:07:42,712
Five centimeters.

753
01:07:42,908 --> 01:07:46,803
All saddles must be complete and intact,
Mr. Obree.

754
01:07:49,853 --> 01:07:52,155
If I use this. First thing I ever designed.

755
01:07:52,221 --> 01:07:56,630
It must be possible to purchase all parts
in the commercial market.

756
01:07:57,246 --> 01:07:58,807
That's just not true.

757
01:07:58,975 --> 01:08:01,910
All the top cyclists have their bikes
personally made for them.

758
01:08:01,983 --> 01:08:03,958
They would cost thousands
to buy in a shop.

759
01:08:04,032 --> 01:08:07,262
Oh, yes.
But if you had thousands you could buy it.

760
01:08:07,328 --> 01:08:08,538
That is the point.

761
01:08:08,608 --> 01:08:10,038
The changes I had to make
to the handlebars

762
01:08:10,113 --> 01:08:12,022
mean it's very difficult
for me to get into position

763
01:08:12,097 --> 01:08:13,920
on a commercial saddle,
'cause they're so big.

764
01:08:13,986 --> 01:08:17,118
There is no rule
about the design of a saddle.

765
01:08:17,186 --> 01:08:21,595
Well, it...
It doesn't break the letter of the rules,

766
01:08:21,667 --> 01:08:25,083
but it breaks the spirit of the rules.

767
01:08:25,892 --> 01:08:29,089
- "The spirit of the rules"?
- Exactly, the spirit.

768
01:08:48,937 --> 01:08:53,345
This is from a 12 year-old's mountain bike,
so we're not breaking any rules.

769
01:08:55,690 --> 01:08:56,638
Sound.

770
01:09:08,109 --> 01:09:10,117
- What's this?
- Bastards!

771
01:09:10,669 --> 01:09:13,157
Hagemann just invented a new rule.

772
01:09:13,229 --> 01:09:16,776
There has to be a gap
between the rider's chest and his hands.

773
01:09:16,846 --> 01:09:18,407
A gap? How much?

774
01:09:19,247 --> 01:09:21,102
He won't quantify it.

775
01:09:21,391 --> 01:09:24,458
Is it strange that I'm the only one
who rides with his chest on his hands?

776
01:09:24,528 --> 01:09:28,326
Yeah, exactly.
I'll tell you what the new rule is.

777
01:09:28,400 --> 01:09:32,362
Nobody called Graeme Obree's allowed
to win the World Championships.

778
01:09:32,433 --> 01:09:34,288
Here's what we're gonna do.

779
01:09:34,353 --> 01:09:37,999
We'll replace it with the tri bars.
They can't object to that.

780
01:09:38,067 --> 01:09:40,849
You can get down low enough on these
and you'll still win.

781
01:09:40,916 --> 01:09:41,996
No.

782
01:09:43,412 --> 01:09:46,227
I'm sticking with Old Faithful
the way she is.

783
01:09:46,869 --> 01:09:48,909
You'll be out of the championship.

784
01:09:49,141 --> 01:09:51,476
I won doing it my way,
I'll lose it doing it my way.

785
01:09:51,541 --> 01:09:53,265
What's that supposed to mean?

786
01:09:53,334 --> 01:09:56,149
That's a lot of bollocks, Graeme,
and you know it.

787
01:09:56,214 --> 01:09:58,670
Look, I'm your manager, right?

788
01:09:58,806 --> 01:10:03,892
It's my job to organize things so you win
and I'm asking you to use these bars

789
01:10:03,960 --> 01:10:07,060
and just go out there
and give it the Obree magic.

790
01:10:07,129 --> 01:10:10,261
Graeme, it's your only chance.

791
01:10:10,873 --> 01:10:14,452
I'm doing it my way, Malky.
Win, lose or get disqualified.

792
01:10:17,562 --> 01:10:19,385
To hell with you, then.

793
01:10:23,964 --> 01:10:24,913
(CROWD CHEERING)

794
01:10:28,509 --> 01:10:32,787
<i>ANNOUNCER: So, a red flag will be raised
by an official if his chest touches his hands.</i>

795
01:10:32,862 --> 01:10:34,651
<i>Three red flags and he's out.</i>

796
01:10:34,718 --> 01:10:37,588
- Come on, Graeme.
- Come on, lad.

797
01:10:58,051 --> 01:11:01,663
<i>I have to say that the whole thing
is utterly mystifying to me.</i>

798
01:11:16,454 --> 01:11:17,796
<i>Only one more flag</i>

799
01:11:17,863 --> 01:11:20,580
<i>and the world champion's championship
will be over.</i>

800
01:11:38,411 --> 01:11:41,827
<i>Obree has fallen and it's a bad one.
They've broken him.</i>

801
01:11:47,661 --> 01:11:51,339
<i>Graeme Obree is now
an ex-world champion.</i>

802
01:12:01,136 --> 01:12:02,478
Graeme?

803
01:12:42,808 --> 01:12:44,215
Malky.

804
01:12:47,897 --> 01:12:51,095
Here, you can take this stuff with you
next time you're down to see Anne.

805
01:12:51,162 --> 01:12:54,359
Oh, take it yourself,
it's got nothing to do with me.

806
01:12:54,426 --> 01:12:57,012
For God's sake, Katie,
it's got nothing to do with me either.

807
01:12:57,083 --> 01:12:59,385
I'm not his manager anymore.

808
01:12:59,451 --> 01:13:02,485
I'm shot of that pig-headed,
bloody-minded pain in the arse.

809
01:13:02,556 --> 01:13:05,754
Which means,
I could not care less about any of this.

810
01:13:06,365 --> 01:13:08,732
You still read it all, though, don't you?

811
01:13:11,422 --> 01:13:13,429
And listen, if you think
that you can shout at me like that

812
01:13:13,502 --> 01:13:17,660
then it's time you move back
to your own flat and sorted yourself out.

813
01:13:20,800 --> 01:13:24,478
<i>ANNOUNCER: Obree has fallen
and it's a bad one. They've broken him.</i>

814
01:13:28,033 --> 01:13:29,309
<i>Only one more flag</i>

815
01:13:29,378 --> 01:13:32,095
<i>and the world champion's championship
will be over.</i>

816
01:13:35,203 --> 01:13:39,132
<i>Obree has fallen and it's a bad one.
They've broken him.</i>

817
01:13:40,228 --> 01:13:41,242
<i>Graeme Obree is now a...</i>

818
01:13:41,316 --> 01:13:42,298
(BANGING ON DOOR)

819
01:13:42,372 --> 01:13:43,550
MAN: Graeme!

820
01:13:46,501 --> 01:13:48,028
Graeme, are you there?

821
01:13:48,357 --> 01:13:49,502
(DOORBELL BUZZING)

822
01:13:57,255 --> 01:13:59,263
I've come down all this way to see you.

823
01:13:59,335 --> 01:14:01,223
You havenae been back for a bit,
Graeme, eh?

824
01:14:02,312 --> 01:14:05,160
I seen you fall on the television, big man.

825
01:14:26,029 --> 01:14:28,648
Did you know my old man got done again?

826
01:14:30,670 --> 01:14:31,815
See...

827
01:14:32,815 --> 01:14:35,368
It was your old boy that done it, Graeme.

828
01:14:36,527 --> 01:14:38,699
Had to have him put away, eh?

829
01:14:41,776 --> 01:14:45,290
Thing is, mate, old boy's not coming back.

830
01:14:46,993 --> 01:14:48,936
'Cause he died inside.

831
01:14:49,938 --> 01:14:51,694
He just couldn't take it.

832
01:14:53,394 --> 01:14:56,362
You did make something of yourself,
Graeme, eh?

833
01:14:56,691 --> 01:14:58,447
For a bit there, eh?

834
01:15:00,211 --> 01:15:02,000
I can see you hiding there.

835
01:15:02,708 --> 01:15:06,255
You're good at hiding and running away,
you silly wee shite.

836
01:15:07,157 --> 01:15:09,547
Running away,
you still think you're too good for us.

837
01:15:09,621 --> 01:15:12,175
That's all you ever do
on that bike of yours, eh?

838
01:15:12,246 --> 01:15:13,621
Run away.

839
01:15:13,814 --> 01:15:16,717
No wonder you're a champion.
See, all that stuff we done to you.

840
01:15:16,791 --> 01:15:18,679
That was just 'cause of your dad,
you do know that, eh?

841
01:15:18,744 --> 01:15:21,744
But you're not really a hero, are you,
Graeme?

842
01:15:21,816 --> 01:15:24,599
You're still a wee shite.
You're a nothing, mate.

843
01:15:24,665 --> 01:15:28,211
And you still think you're too good for us.
You're a nobody.

844
01:15:29,625 --> 01:15:31,414
You're pathetic.

845
01:15:55,391 --> 01:15:56,340
(SHOUTS )

846
01:16:02,176 --> 01:16:04,282
<i>MALKY: Graeme!</i>

847
01:16:12,322 --> 01:16:14,711
<i>MALKY: Graeme!
ANNE: Graeme!</i>

848
01:16:17,891 --> 01:16:20,096
<i>MAN: I saw you fall.</i>

849
01:16:25,637 --> 01:16:27,525
Oh, my. Stay there.

850
01:16:33,671 --> 01:16:34,783
(GRAEME GROANING)

851
01:16:35,143 --> 01:16:38,526
Listen. Listen to me, I'm going for help.

852
01:16:39,560 --> 01:16:42,561
All right, an ambulance, a doctor.
Do you understand me?

853
01:16:43,112 --> 01:16:47,456
I'll be back as soon as I can.
Just lie there and take it easy, all right?

854
01:16:47,530 --> 01:16:49,897
Wait here, I'll call an ambulance.

855
01:16:51,146 --> 01:16:52,259
(GRAEME COUGHING)

856
01:17:06,798 --> 01:17:08,686
Anne. Anne.

857
01:17:29,074 --> 01:17:31,944
Graeme, this can't go on.
We have to do something.

858
01:17:32,051 --> 01:17:33,906
It's all right, I'm okay.

859
01:17:35,091 --> 01:17:37,645
No, you're not okay.

860
01:17:39,572 --> 01:17:43,763
Hey, this is an ex-world champion
you're talking to.

861
01:17:45,237 --> 01:17:48,751
- There's not many people can say that.
- Graeme, you need help.

862
01:17:49,206 --> 01:17:51,792
I told you before,

863
01:17:51,863 --> 01:17:55,092
I'll sort myself out in my own time.

864
01:17:56,279 --> 01:17:59,279
Yeah, that'll make a great epitaph.

865
01:18:51,907 --> 01:18:53,336
That's very good.

866
01:18:53,411 --> 01:18:55,037
Hey, how you doing?

867
01:18:57,668 --> 01:18:59,741
Hey? Hey?

868
01:19:06,406 --> 01:19:09,341
You've been working hard. You should rest
when you come in, you know.

869
01:19:09,414 --> 01:19:11,716
Especially since you're
paying the bills these days.

870
01:19:11,782 --> 01:19:15,395
- Have you been a good boy?
- Yeah, we both have.

871
01:19:17,928 --> 01:19:20,929
I phoned the courier people.
I'm starting Monday.

872
01:19:21,001 --> 01:19:24,514
It's only a month's contract,
but at least it's something.

873
01:19:24,585 --> 01:19:26,560
Back to square one, eh?

874
01:19:26,986 --> 01:19:28,579
(DOORBELL BUZZING)

875
01:19:28,650 --> 01:19:29,927
I'll get it.

876
01:19:34,539 --> 01:19:35,968
"Dear Mr. Obree.

877
01:19:36,043 --> 01:19:40,834
"The track at Hamar Stadium in Norway
is being resurfaced.

878
01:19:40,909 --> 01:19:44,422
"In recognition of your historic
cycling achievements at the stadium

879
01:19:44,493 --> 01:19:47,177
"breaking the one-hour record
and smashing the world record

880
01:19:47,246 --> 01:19:49,254
"to become World Pursuit Champion,

881
01:19:49,326 --> 01:19:53,451
"we hope you will accept
this piece of the old track

882
01:19:53,520 --> 01:19:56,171
"as a souvenir of your wonderful triumph.

883
01:19:56,240 --> 01:19:58,444
"It has been a pleasure
writing to you with this news

884
01:19:58,512 --> 01:20:00,520
"and I wish you the very best
for your future.

885
01:20:00,593 --> 01:20:03,212
"Yours sincerely, Irga Olsen."

886
01:20:14,547 --> 01:20:18,988
Graeme, the boss wants to see you.
Something about a special delivery.

887
01:20:43,994 --> 01:20:46,711
- Graeme, how are you?
- I'm all right.

888
01:20:47,258 --> 01:20:51,536
- Got a delivery for you, needs a signature.
- I'll get my glasses. Come in.

889
01:20:54,043 --> 01:20:56,826
Look I'm not stupid. What's this in aid of?

890
01:20:58,364 --> 01:21:01,561
If I suggested we get together,
what would you have said?

891
01:21:13,695 --> 01:21:14,939
What's going on?

892
01:21:15,008 --> 01:21:18,139
I told you.
I'll be leaving at the end of the month.

893
01:21:18,209 --> 01:21:19,321
Tea?

894
01:21:22,209 --> 01:21:23,420
I'm going up north.

895
01:21:23,489 --> 01:21:26,621
Some friends of mine from
the Merchant Navy have got me a job.

896
01:21:26,690 --> 01:21:29,691
Teaching disturbed kids how to sail a boat.

897
01:21:30,050 --> 01:21:32,866
Oh, is that what I am? A disturbed kid?

898
01:21:38,084 --> 01:21:41,947
I was gonna tell you about her.

899
01:21:43,589 --> 01:21:46,011
- GRAEME: Your wife?
- Aye.

900
01:21:46,342 --> 01:21:49,190
- What happened to her?
- She drowned.

901
01:21:55,432 --> 01:21:58,847
I was 39 when I met her.

902
01:21:59,976 --> 01:22:03,872
I left the Merchant Navy and I was
studying for the ministry in Australia

903
01:22:03,946 --> 01:22:06,532
and one summer's morning
down by Sydney Harbour

904
01:22:06,602 --> 01:22:10,345
I saw this young woman
not much more than half my age and...

905
01:22:11,307 --> 01:22:12,616
Oh, boy,

906
01:22:13,804 --> 01:22:16,488
I felt as if I was struck by lightning.

907
01:22:18,156 --> 01:22:23,013
All I knew was I wanted to
spend the rest of my life with her.

908
01:22:23,085 --> 01:22:25,704
Amazingly, she felt the same way.

909
01:22:28,303 --> 01:22:31,565
We only had three short years together,
that's all.

910
01:22:32,431 --> 01:22:35,531
You said she drowned. Was it an accident?

911
01:22:35,632 --> 01:22:38,928
Oh, no. She could swim like a fish.

912
01:22:48,275 --> 01:22:50,479
<i>WOMAN: Graeme.</i>

913
01:23:02,197 --> 01:23:04,238
She killed herself, Graeme.

914
01:23:06,615 --> 01:23:08,982
She had the same illness as you.

915
01:23:10,903 --> 01:23:13,075
She couldn't take it anymore.

916
01:23:14,200 --> 01:23:17,016
She said it was like being in a swamp.

917
01:23:18,360 --> 01:23:22,998
Alone in the darkness,
slowly being sucked down, inch by inch,

918
01:23:23,065 --> 01:23:25,521
the life squeezed out of her

919
01:23:25,594 --> 01:23:29,489
and knowing that nobody was ever
gonna come and save her

920
01:23:29,563 --> 01:23:32,215
because nobody knew she was even there.

921
01:23:33,532 --> 01:23:36,380
You see, there were things in her life,

922
01:23:36,444 --> 01:23:39,740
in her childhood, she would just,
would not talk about.

923
01:23:41,438 --> 01:23:43,325
I thought, maybe...

924
01:23:43,390 --> 01:23:47,514
Maybe if we had a bit more time together,
I could have done something.

925
01:23:52,255 --> 01:23:55,190
- We can talk about it.
- What's the point in talking about it?

926
01:23:55,264 --> 01:23:57,468
Have you ever talked about it before?

927
01:23:58,080 --> 01:24:00,634
So, why do you think there's no point?

928
01:24:13,956 --> 01:24:18,812
They made me feel worthless. Like...
Like I was nothing.

929
01:24:20,709 --> 01:24:23,579
Just something to be...

930
01:24:25,638 --> 01:24:26,653
Used?

931
01:24:29,127 --> 01:24:30,688
Who's "they," Graeme?

932
01:24:33,736 --> 01:24:38,723
It's all right, you know, it's like...
It's like your first time on a bike.

933
01:24:39,881 --> 01:24:43,078
Just keep going. You'll be fine.

934
01:25:23,250 --> 01:25:26,284
- Are you gonna talk to him again?
- Probably.

935
01:25:27,730 --> 01:25:31,277
Although he says
I should see a professional therapist.

936
01:25:31,348 --> 01:25:33,006
What do you think?

937
01:25:36,628 --> 01:25:40,077
Maybe you could fix me up
with someone at the hospital.

938
01:25:40,854 --> 01:25:42,283
Yeah, I could.

939
01:25:46,743 --> 01:25:50,126
- Malky called today.
- Yeah? What was he saying?

940
01:25:50,487 --> 01:25:52,211
Just wanted a chat.

941
01:25:52,568 --> 01:25:54,870
It's funny,
I was thinking I should give him a call.

942
01:25:54,936 --> 01:25:55,885
Yeah?

943
01:25:57,273 --> 01:26:00,307
See what he thinks about going in
for some wee events.

944
01:26:01,081 --> 01:26:04,311
Nothing serious, just a toe in the water.

945
01:26:45,283 --> 01:26:46,712
Bloody hell.

946
01:27:06,214 --> 01:27:10,623
CROWD: (CHANTING) Superman,
Superman, Superman, Superman...

947
01:27:25,738 --> 01:27:28,259
<i>ANNOUNCER: The crowd is chanting,
"Superman, Superman"</i>

948
01:27:28,331 --> 01:27:30,787
<i>and Obree's new position does indeed...</i>

949
01:27:30,860 --> 01:27:32,070
- Hiya.
- How are you doing?

950
01:27:32,139 --> 01:27:33,088
All right.

951
01:27:36,429 --> 01:27:38,851
Oh, aye, Sparkling Highland Water, please.

952
01:27:42,126 --> 01:27:44,548
Okay, so what's the plan?

953
01:27:46,735 --> 01:27:48,426
What do you think?

954
01:27:51,728 --> 01:27:53,289
Forget Colinelli.

955
01:27:53,713 --> 01:27:57,707
The only person you need to worry about
is that stubborn bugger Graeme Obree.

956
01:28:02,354 --> 01:28:05,038
Come on, you beauty. Just one more time.

957
01:28:06,995 --> 01:28:09,451
So, no signals till halfway.

958
01:28:23,383 --> 01:28:24,627
MAN: On you go, boy!

959
01:28:29,976 --> 01:28:31,220
(CROWD CHEERING)

960
01:28:48,123 --> 01:28:50,971
<i>ANNOUNCER: Obree is 0.7 seconds down
on his first lap.</i>

961
01:28:51,036 --> 01:28:54,036
<i>He's not making it very easy
on himself or us.</i>

962
01:29:34,692 --> 01:29:35,740
Excuse me.

963
01:29:37,381 --> 01:29:39,585
<i>ANNOUNCER: This is a man
who's got something to prove.</i>

964
01:29:39,653 --> 01:29:40,831
Any chance of a lager there?

965
01:29:40,902 --> 01:29:42,975
<i>What a recovery! Two laps...</i>

966
01:29:52,552 --> 01:29:53,796
Go on, son!

967
01:29:53,960 --> 01:29:57,703
<i>Deficient air here 8,000 feet up
